<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920129-0171</DOCNO><DOCID>920129-0171.</DOCID><HL>   REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):   `We've Been Robbed'</HL><DATE>01/29/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><CO>   LABOR</CO><IN>MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)</IN><NS>MUTUAL FUNDS (FND)LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)UNITED NATIONS (UNN)</NS><RE>EASTERN EUROPE (EEU)EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)RUSSIA (RS)COMMONWEALTH OF INDEPENDENT STATES (UR)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   In the bad old days, Soviet diplomats at the UnitedNations routinely used their jobs as spying posts. It turnsout that such extracurricular work for the KGB wasn't a verygood deal: Diplomats, the U.N. staff bulletin reports, &quot;werecompelled to surrender two-thirds or more of their salariesas well as installation grants, education and benefits andper diem allowances to their Soviet handlers.&quot; Just likeSoviet athletes. Under a 1980 agreement with the U.N., theU.N. transferred pension moneys directly to Moscow, which inturn promised to take care of the diplomats' retirement -- apromise that yielded &quot;pensions&quot; worth, at the ruble'sdevalued rate, $5 or $10 a month.   Something very American must have rubbed off on thesedisgruntled snoops, because in their revenge they areconsidering this nation's weapon of choice: the lawsuit. Thestaff newspaper reports some 1,400 former Soviet staffmembers are preparing a class-action suit for $40 million inback pension payments and interest against the U.N. PensionFund. Their argument: The U.N. violated the principles of adocument it created itself, the 1948 Universal Declaration ofHuman Rights.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We have been robbed,&quot; a Moscow spokesman for the grouptold the U.N. Staff Report in Moscow. (Included in theirnumbers is the widow of Victor Leslovsky, whom many suspectedas having been KGB station chief at the U.N.) &quot;No othertotalitarian regime has ever gone to so cynical a robbery ofits loyal and patriotically minded citizens,&quot; complained alitigant. Who could argue with that?   Reached by phone, the U.N. Pension Fund said it had heardnothing about a lawsuit as yet. The plaintiffs reportedlyplan to take their case to the International Court of Justicebut they oughtn't rule out the U.S. as a venue. We havewatched many American courts hear sillier cases than thisone. The retirees have also found in the $9 billion U.N.Pension Fund the first requisite for such a suit: a fattarget.</TEXT></DOC>